1
00:00:11,578 --> 00:00:15,081
FUKUOKA, 2005

2
00:00:29,195 --> 00:00:30,763
Hi, there.

3
00:00:30,764 --> 00:00:31,965
Hello.

4
00:00:39,205 --> 00:00:40,373
Mari,

5
00:00:41,241 --> 00:00:42,975
are you still playing out here?

6
00:00:42,976 --> 00:00:44,677
MARI KODA (10)

7
00:00:45,545 --> 00:00:47,981
Did you finish your summer break homework?

8
00:00:48,548 --> 00:00:49,549
I already did.

9
00:00:50,083 --> 00:00:52,619
How about your craft project?
You need to turn it in, right?

10
00:00:53,453 --> 00:00:56,188
I still haven't collected
enough milk cartons, yet.

11
00:00:56,189 --> 00:01:00,025
I'm sure you can make do
with what you have. You bought so many.

12
00:01:00,026 --> 00:01:01,693
No, I can't.

13
00:01:01,694 --> 00:01:04,397
I'm making a boat, you know.
I don't have enough.

14
00:01:07,967 --> 00:01:11,504
Then, why don't you go buy
two cartons of milk.

15
00:01:12,138 --> 00:01:13,872
I'm making stew for dinner.

16
00:01:13,873 --> 00:01:15,642
In this hot weather?

17
00:01:16,209 --> 00:01:18,344
I'm doing it for you, honey.

18
00:01:19,379 --> 00:01:20,447
Here.

19
00:01:27,287 --> 00:01:28,588
Come on, hurry up.

20
00:01:36,729 --> 00:01:38,031
Oh, I almost forgot.

21
00:01:39,299 --> 00:01:40,567
Stop by Semaul on the way home.

22
00:01:41,401 --> 00:01:42,902
Semaul?

23
00:01:43,470 --> 00:01:44,704
Buy some green chili peppers.

24
00:01:45,338 --> 00:01:47,107
Sure. See you.

25
00:01:49,676 --> 00:01:51,511
What's up with her?

26
00:02:10,964 --> 00:02:12,764
Who are you, my dear?

27
00:02:12,765 --> 00:02:14,000
Oh, I see.

28
00:02:14,567 --> 00:02:17,637
I see what you're doing there.

29
00:02:18,438 --> 00:02:20,739
CHILI PEPPERS 348 YEN

30
00:02:20,740 --> 00:02:22,741
Give it to me. Come on!

31
00:02:22,742 --> 00:02:25,345
Oh, you came outside all by yourself?

32
00:02:27,046 --> 00:02:29,047
Oh, boy!

33
00:02:29,048 --> 00:02:31,517
Seriously? Another loss?

34
00:02:31,518 --> 00:02:34,487
SEMAUL KOREAN GROCERIES

35
00:02:37,724 --> 00:02:39,359
350 YEN PER BAG

36
00:02:42,662 --> 00:02:44,664
KIMCHI

37
00:02:56,576 --> 00:02:58,243
350 YEN PER

38
00:02:58,244 --> 00:03:00,445
JIN RAMEN

39
00:03:00,446 --> 00:03:01,915
‎KOREAN SAKE

40
00:03:05,285 --> 00:03:06,518
‎SEASONED SOYBEAN PASTE, RED CHILI PASTE

41
00:03:06,519 --> 00:03:07,620
KIMPAP

42
00:03:15,762 --> 00:03:16,763
Hi, sweetie.

43
00:03:38,451 --> 00:03:41,187
SHINJUKU, TOKYO 2025

44
00:03:43,423 --> 00:03:46,192
- See you.
- See you, then.

45
00:03:49,429 --> 00:03:51,231
Mr. Arikino, can I have a minute?

46
00:03:52,265 --> 00:03:53,365
Sure. What is it?

47
00:03:53,366 --> 00:03:56,636
I'm still pursuing Volunteer
from the kidnapping case.

48
00:03:58,705 --> 00:04:01,506
Take the baby
to the mainland and hand him over

49
00:04:01,507 --> 00:04:03,909
to the person waiting at the airport.

50
00:04:03,910 --> 00:04:06,878
It seems Mr. Shakuno here
felt a sense of defeat

51
00:04:06,879 --> 00:04:10,250
because Miss Koda
received all the credit for the case.

52
00:04:10,817 --> 00:04:13,819
So, he's been gathering information
on Volunteer ever since.

53
00:04:13,820 --> 00:04:14,921
That's not true at all.

54
00:04:15,622 --> 00:04:19,392
I'm not doing it for a promotion.
Because this is our priority case...

55
00:04:21,327 --> 00:04:22,262
Move.

56
00:04:22,996 --> 00:04:26,698
There's a possibility that Volunteer
is involved in citizenship trade.

57
00:04:26,699 --> 00:04:30,336
So, I'm going to interview
Wang Jianbin's former colleagues.

58
00:04:30,903 --> 00:04:33,072
Would you mind coming along?

59
00:04:36,576 --> 00:04:37,477
Mr. Arikino?

60
00:04:38,244 --> 00:04:40,812
What do you think? Can you come with me?

61
00:04:40,813 --> 00:04:41,847
Sure, I can.

62
00:04:41,848 --> 00:04:44,651
Thank you. I'll let you know
once I have the date.

63
00:04:46,052 --> 00:04:47,053
Okay.

64
00:04:48,621 --> 00:04:49,656
Excuse me, then.

65
00:04:57,964 --> 00:05:01,099
I wonder if something's
going on with Mr. Arikino.

66
00:05:01,100 --> 00:05:02,969
He wasn't quite himself today, was he?

67
00:05:03,536 --> 00:05:06,706
He seemed distracted
even during the questioning.

68
00:05:07,307 --> 00:05:09,175
I wonder if something happened.

69
00:05:13,479 --> 00:05:14,446
Listen, Miss Imai...

70
00:05:14,447 --> 00:05:15,714
TOKYO METROPOLITAN POLICE
INTERPRETATION CENTER

71
00:05:15,715 --> 00:05:18,417
I found a Vietnamese restaurant
that serves amazing <i>banh xeo.</i>

72
00:05:18,418 --> 00:05:20,585
- Would you like to go sometime?
- Where is it?

73
00:05:20,586 --> 00:05:21,620
In Takadanobaba.

74
00:05:21,621 --> 00:05:23,822
I know that one.
I've been wanting to go there.

75
00:05:23,823 --> 00:05:26,225
We're going then. I'll buy.

76
00:05:27,327 --> 00:05:29,662
Sounds great! When are we going?

77
00:05:30,730 --> 00:05:32,698
Do you want to come, too?

78
00:05:32,699 --> 00:05:35,168
Of course I do! But is there a problem?

79
00:05:36,069 --> 00:05:38,371
Um... no. I'm so thrilled.

80
00:05:38,971 --> 00:05:40,038
All right then.

81
00:05:40,039 --> 00:05:42,342
Thanks for the treat.

82
00:05:43,309 --> 00:05:44,577
Mr. Arikino?

83
00:05:45,511 --> 00:05:48,414
Thanks for coming to my place
for the party the other day.

84
00:05:49,716 --> 00:05:51,784
Would you like to go have
some great <i>banh xeo?</i>

85
00:05:52,385 --> 00:05:53,352
Huh?

86
00:05:53,353 --> 00:05:55,520
Kurosu is buying.

87
00:05:55,521 --> 00:05:57,824
- Well, um...
- Mr. Arikino?

88
00:05:59,625 --> 00:06:03,329
Tell me, Miss Imai,
has something made you cry recently?

89
00:06:04,163 --> 00:06:05,231
What?

90
00:06:06,532 --> 00:06:08,634
That's really close to sexual harassment.

91
00:06:12,605 --> 00:06:15,541
I'm so sorry. It's nothing.

92
00:06:19,345 --> 00:06:21,914
- What was that about?
- I have no idea.

93
00:06:23,483 --> 00:06:25,118
Thank God!

94
00:06:30,289 --> 00:06:31,557
Miss Koda?

95
00:06:33,126 --> 00:06:35,628
Whoa, you totally scared me!

96
00:06:36,295 --> 00:06:38,965
Why didn't you tell me you were here?

97
00:06:48,641 --> 00:06:49,675
Can I have one?

98
00:06:51,844 --> 00:06:52,845
I mean, your cigarette.

99
00:06:54,213 --> 00:06:55,248
I thought you quit.

100
00:06:57,116 --> 00:06:59,218
I still smoke every now and then.

101
00:07:11,664 --> 00:07:12,565
Here.

102
00:07:19,038 --> 00:07:20,840
I have no idea what happened.

103
00:07:22,241 --> 00:07:23,609
But you shouldn't, you know...

104
00:07:24,310 --> 00:07:25,945
you shouldn't brood by yourself.

105
00:07:31,584 --> 00:07:34,220
Remember what he used to say?

106
00:07:37,924 --> 00:07:38,891
Ryo.

107
00:07:41,594 --> 00:07:43,329
What the heck are you doing?

108
00:07:46,432 --> 00:07:48,634
You're brooding by yourself again,
aren't you?

109
00:07:51,437 --> 00:07:53,806
Just thinking about it
will only frustrate you.

110
00:07:55,208 --> 00:07:59,011
You should talk to someone
so the fog in your head clears.

111
00:08:21,400 --> 00:08:25,338
I'M LEAVING. MAKE SURE YOU LOCK THE DOOR
WHEN YOU LEAVE.

112
00:08:26,405 --> 00:08:27,907
I wish he had woken me up.

113
00:08:32,845 --> 00:08:35,781
MARI KODA: ARIKEENO, I NEED YOUR HELP

114
00:08:47,760 --> 00:08:48,728
Whoa...

115
00:08:50,129 --> 00:08:51,162
Oh!

116
00:08:51,163 --> 00:08:52,365
Hi, Arikeeno!

117
00:08:52,899 --> 00:08:54,566
You made it!

118
00:08:54,567 --> 00:08:56,134
What's going on here?

119
00:08:56,135 --> 00:09:00,506
I wanted you to help me
clean up this mess. Here.

120
00:09:02,975 --> 00:09:05,410
It looks like a typhoon passed through.

121
00:09:05,411 --> 00:09:09,014
The Nepalis had an all-night party

122
00:09:09,015 --> 00:09:11,082
at the restaurant over there.

123
00:09:11,083 --> 00:09:14,286
Some were making noise outside,
and a few even got into a fight.

124
00:09:14,287 --> 00:09:15,988
And that's how this mess happened.

125
00:09:16,789 --> 00:09:18,090
Thanks so much in advance.

126
00:09:21,460 --> 00:09:24,764
Mr. Wada, why are you helping with this?

127
00:09:25,531 --> 00:09:27,667
You should report to the police.

128
00:09:28,734 --> 00:09:31,871
Foreigners make so much trouble.
Look at this mess.

129
00:09:32,838 --> 00:09:34,941
Please follow our social protocol.

130
00:09:35,508 --> 00:09:36,375
I'm so sorry.

131
00:09:37,176 --> 00:09:39,644
You're in Japan, for heaven's sake.
Do you understand?

132
00:09:39,645 --> 00:09:42,080
We are so sorry.

133
00:09:42,081 --> 00:09:46,352
I'll make sure everything
gets completely cleaned up around here.

134
00:09:49,855 --> 00:09:50,756
I'm sorry.

135
00:09:51,857 --> 00:09:53,025
I'm sorry.

136
00:09:55,328 --> 00:09:57,663
What an incredible mess!

137
00:09:59,999 --> 00:10:01,366
You know what, Pujara?

138
00:10:01,367 --> 00:10:04,169
How about we separate
the cans and bottles?

139
00:10:04,170 --> 00:10:07,173
- Oops, I mixed them all up.
- No problem at all.

140
00:10:21,988 --> 00:10:24,624
Ouch, my back!

141
00:10:31,831 --> 00:10:34,400
I guess it's good now.

142
00:10:35,001 --> 00:10:36,435
Thanks.

143
00:10:47,346 --> 00:10:48,581
He's mad at me, isn't he?

144
00:10:50,416 --> 00:10:52,584
He's fine. Don't worry.

145
00:10:52,585 --> 00:10:55,488
It's just that Mr. Wada is super shy.
So, don't worry.

146
00:10:56,522 --> 00:10:59,424
I don't know how to thank you.

147
00:10:59,425 --> 00:11:03,595
Never mind. We all help each other out
when we're in trouble.

148
00:11:03,596 --> 00:11:08,534
But next time when it looks like
something like this is going to happen,

149
00:11:09,301 --> 00:11:11,136
you have to confront the customer.

150
00:11:11,137 --> 00:11:13,005
Yes, ma'am. I won't let this happen again.

151
00:11:15,975 --> 00:11:17,610
Pujara, come in for a bowl of <i>soba.</i>

152
00:11:18,110 --> 00:11:19,911
After that, you'll get a good scolding.

153
00:11:19,912 --> 00:11:20,846
Yes, sir.

154
00:11:21,947 --> 00:11:24,316
Thank you, Mari and Mari's friend.

155
00:11:26,085 --> 00:11:27,752
- Pujara, come.
- Okay.

156
00:11:27,753 --> 00:11:29,088
See you.

157
00:11:33,592 --> 00:11:35,026
Thanks so much, Arikeeno.

158
00:11:35,027 --> 00:11:36,128
No problem.

159
00:11:36,696 --> 00:11:39,865
I was able to sweat the alcohol
from last night out of my system.

160
00:11:41,801 --> 00:11:42,635
Very cool.

161
00:11:43,636 --> 00:11:46,105
Well, well, well. Shall we go
our separate ways then?

162
00:11:47,840 --> 00:11:48,974
Um...

163
00:11:50,643 --> 00:11:51,977
Since we're here anyway,

164
00:11:54,046 --> 00:11:55,014
how about we grab a coffee?

165
00:11:56,082 --> 00:11:56,916
What?

166
00:11:57,850 --> 00:11:58,851
I'm treating you this time.

167
00:12:02,521 --> 00:12:04,690
Don't you think
you're ordering a bit too much?

168
00:12:05,257 --> 00:12:06,759
No problem. I'm going to eat it all.

169
00:12:08,027 --> 00:12:10,428
That's not the issue.

170
00:12:10,429 --> 00:12:13,131
Here's your <i>bibimbap.</i>

171
00:12:13,132 --> 00:12:15,900
Mari, my dear, what happened today?

172
00:12:15,901 --> 00:12:18,336
I've never seen you this early, you know.

173
00:12:18,337 --> 00:12:20,940
I know. It's my day off today.

174
00:12:23,776 --> 00:12:26,078
And maybe
you brought your boyfriend along?

175
00:12:26,746 --> 00:12:28,147
It's not like that at all,

176
00:12:28,914 --> 00:12:30,482
but it is a date.

177
00:12:30,483 --> 00:12:33,618
Honey, don't disturb them.

178
00:12:33,619 --> 00:12:35,387
I know, I know.

179
00:12:36,255 --> 00:12:37,689
I'd hate to disturb,

180
00:12:37,690 --> 00:12:40,025
so I'm leaving you alone.

181
00:12:40,693 --> 00:12:42,360
Enjoy your meal.

182
00:12:42,361 --> 00:12:44,730
Hurry up!

183
00:12:48,367 --> 00:12:50,536
- Kyushu?
- Yep.

184
00:12:51,570 --> 00:12:53,304
Didn't I tell you before?

185
00:12:53,305 --> 00:12:55,708
I'm from Fukuoka.

186
00:12:56,375 --> 00:12:57,877
Is that right?

187
00:12:59,178 --> 00:13:00,546
I heard it for the first time.

188
00:13:02,715 --> 00:13:05,451
Shall I speak in the Hakata dialect?

189
00:13:06,519 --> 00:13:07,720
You don't have to.

190
00:13:09,855 --> 00:13:12,057
Here's your <i>tonkasu.</i>

191
00:13:12,958 --> 00:13:15,461
- Make sure you eat a lot.
- Thanks. I will.

192
00:13:17,062 --> 00:13:17,897
By the way...

193
00:13:18,664 --> 00:13:20,999
Did you know that "<i>tonkatsu,</i>"
or pork cutlet,

194
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:22,868
is called "<i>tonkasu</i>" in Korea?

195
00:13:23,702 --> 00:13:25,271
<i>- Tonkasu?</i>
- That's right.

196
00:13:26,038 --> 00:13:28,607
And the word for "<i>ramen,</i>" as in noodles,
is "<i>ramyon</i>".

197
00:13:29,141 --> 00:13:31,176
"<i>Nattō</i>" for fermented soybeans is "<i>natto</i>",

198
00:13:31,177 --> 00:13:33,779
and "<i>chomiryō</i>", or seasonings,
is "<i>chomiryo</i>".

199
00:13:34,446 --> 00:13:35,346
Really?

200
00:13:35,347 --> 00:13:38,818
The pronunciations are a bit different,
but the meanings are the same.

201
00:13:50,729 --> 00:13:53,232
What's wrong, Arikeeno? You're not eating?

202
00:13:53,899 --> 00:13:55,601
I'm eating.

203
00:13:57,469 --> 00:13:58,571
But...

204
00:14:00,639 --> 00:14:03,108
you were crying the other day,
weren't you?

205
00:14:07,346 --> 00:14:08,514
Was I?

206
00:14:09,181 --> 00:14:10,082
Why were you crying?

207
00:14:13,485 --> 00:14:15,688
It's been on my mind ever since.

208
00:14:18,490 --> 00:14:20,893
You're pretty straightforward, aren't you?

209
00:14:22,361 --> 00:14:23,195
All right then,

210
00:14:24,129 --> 00:14:26,465
let me give you one piece of advice.

211
00:14:27,399 --> 00:14:31,637
That kind of thing
should be left untouched.

212
00:14:33,138 --> 00:14:34,039
Actually,

213
00:14:35,374 --> 00:14:38,077
you're the one
who's always straightforward.

214
00:14:39,144 --> 00:14:41,113
You do have a point right there.

215
00:14:44,316 --> 00:14:45,150
Well,

216
00:14:46,919 --> 00:14:48,053
if you'd rather not talk about it...

217
00:14:50,256 --> 00:14:51,090
No,

218
00:14:52,491 --> 00:14:53,492
I don't mind.

219
00:14:54,660 --> 00:14:57,062
Well, you know...

220
00:14:57,997 --> 00:14:59,565
Let's say
you're living in a foreign country.

221
00:15:00,466 --> 00:15:04,270
<i>And you meet someone
who has something in common with you</i>

222
00:15:05,271 --> 00:15:08,473
<i>like a name or where you're from.</i>

223
00:15:08,474 --> 00:15:09,874
Just that alone

224
00:15:09,875 --> 00:15:13,212
can be a huge support and encouragement.

225
00:15:14,546 --> 00:15:17,950
I realized that even more
through Tien's incident.

226
00:15:20,953 --> 00:15:22,021
And it reminded me

227
00:15:24,156 --> 00:15:26,125
of someone important to me.

228
00:15:33,232 --> 00:15:35,167
Here's something.

229
00:15:35,701 --> 00:15:36,936
Take a look at this.

230
00:15:40,806 --> 00:15:41,674
Ta-da!

231
00:15:43,676 --> 00:15:45,911
I was already cute as a child,
don't you think?

232
00:15:49,415 --> 00:15:50,282
And the lady next to you is?

233
00:15:52,718 --> 00:15:55,387
This lady is... my <i>eonni.</i>

234
00:15:55,921 --> 00:15:58,190
- <i>Eonni?</i>
- My big sister.

235
00:16:00,759 --> 00:16:01,794
You had a big sister?

236
00:16:03,128 --> 00:16:05,464
She's not my real sister,

237
00:16:06,332 --> 00:16:08,033
but she was like a sister to me.

238
00:16:11,270 --> 00:16:12,404
Her name was...

239
00:16:13,405 --> 00:16:14,373
Soohyun.

240
00:16:15,307 --> 00:16:16,241
Soohyun?

241
00:16:16,942 --> 00:16:17,810
Hi, sweetheart.

242
00:16:18,677 --> 00:16:20,079
What are you looking for?

243
00:16:20,846 --> 00:16:23,849
Um... Gre... green chili peppers.

244
00:16:24,516 --> 00:16:25,751
Green chili peppers?

245
00:16:27,319 --> 00:16:28,287
Come over here.

246
00:16:33,359 --> 00:16:35,961
Among these,

247
00:16:37,796 --> 00:16:39,064
these ones are the best.

248
00:16:44,303 --> 00:16:46,171
How do you know that they're the best?

249
00:16:48,140 --> 00:16:50,174
Fresh green chili peppers are firm,

250
00:16:50,175 --> 00:16:53,712
glossy, and have a vibrant,
solid skin throughout.

251
00:16:54,380 --> 00:16:55,314
Really?

252
00:16:55,914 --> 00:16:57,316
Thank you.

253
00:16:59,485 --> 00:17:02,153
What happened with school?
Are you on summer break now?

254
00:17:02,154 --> 00:17:03,589
Yes, I am. How about you?

255
00:17:04,223 --> 00:17:05,724
My high school is on break, too.

256
00:17:06,658 --> 00:17:07,893
Oh, I almost forgot this.

257
00:17:08,861 --> 00:17:10,729
- Here.
- Thank you.

258
00:17:14,066 --> 00:17:15,733
How do you read this?

259
00:17:15,734 --> 00:17:16,667
250 YEN PER BAG

260
00:17:16,668 --> 00:17:18,837
- "<i>Yumilgwa.</i>"
- "<i>Yumilgwa.</i>"

261
00:17:20,072 --> 00:17:21,240
Then...

262
00:17:22,274 --> 00:17:23,741
How about this one?

263
00:17:23,742 --> 00:17:26,145
"<i>Kkaeyot kanjong.</i>"

264
00:17:27,146 --> 00:17:28,446
How about... this one?

265
00:17:28,447 --> 00:17:29,414
LETTUCE 150 YEN

266
00:17:29,415 --> 00:17:30,415
"<i>Yang sangchu.</i>"

267
00:17:30,416 --> 00:17:32,350
"<i>Yang sangchu.</i>"

268
00:17:32,351 --> 00:17:33,452
How about this one?

269
00:17:34,219 --> 00:17:37,021
- "<i>Cheongyang gochu.</i>"
- "<i>Cheongyang gochu.</i>"

270
00:17:37,022 --> 00:17:38,757
- You're very good.
- And this one?

271
00:17:39,558 --> 00:17:41,994
- "<i>Hanguk kim.</i>"
- "<i>Hanguk kim.</i>"

272
00:17:43,896 --> 00:17:46,798
There are some words
that are very similar to Japanese.

273
00:17:46,799 --> 00:17:47,900
Very similar words?

274
00:17:48,634 --> 00:17:50,001
For example,

275
00:17:50,002 --> 00:17:52,471
the word for giraffe is "<i>kirin</i>" in Korean,
just like in Japanese.

276
00:17:53,038 --> 00:17:56,508
- They're the same?
- And "<i>kaban</i>" for bags is "<i>kaban</i>",

277
00:17:57,443 --> 00:17:58,744
and "<i>sansuu</i>" for arithmatic is "<i>sansu</i>".

278
00:17:59,411 --> 00:18:01,579
"<i>Ramen</i>" is "<i>ramyon</i>",

279
00:18:01,580 --> 00:18:03,449
and "<i>tonkatsu</i>" is "<i>tonkasu</i>".

280
00:18:04,049 --> 00:18:06,885
They're almost the same.
Are there any other words?

281
00:18:07,619 --> 00:18:08,987
What else?

282
00:18:11,590 --> 00:18:12,925
"<i>Yakusoku</i>" for promise.

283
00:18:13,559 --> 00:18:15,193
<i>Yakusoku...</i>

284
00:18:15,194 --> 00:18:17,762
"<i>Yakusoku</i>" is "<i>yagsog</i>".

285
00:18:17,763 --> 00:18:18,831
"<i>Yagsog.</i>"

286
00:18:22,901 --> 00:18:24,169
Mmm, yum!

287
00:18:25,437 --> 00:18:26,838
One more <i>tonkasu,</i> please.

288
00:18:26,839 --> 00:18:29,141
<i>Tonkasu?</i> Got it.

289
00:18:30,309 --> 00:18:33,078
You really have an incredible appetite.

290
00:18:35,180 --> 00:18:36,515
I'm remembering

291
00:18:37,516 --> 00:18:41,086
how they let me try
all kinds of Korean food at their shop.

292
00:18:41,887 --> 00:18:45,156
It was so fun
that I kept going back there every day

293
00:18:45,157 --> 00:18:46,992
during the summer break.

294
00:18:49,027 --> 00:18:50,361
What's this?

295
00:18:50,362 --> 00:18:52,965
It's a Korean dish called "<i>beondegi</i>".

296
00:18:54,666 --> 00:18:57,468
- These are silkworms.
- Dad, you're scaring her.

297
00:18:57,469 --> 00:18:59,071
I'm so sorry.

298
00:19:00,072 --> 00:19:04,575
Back in the days when food was scarce,

299
00:19:04,576 --> 00:19:06,945
these were a precious source of nutrition.

300
00:19:07,946 --> 00:19:08,780
I want to try.

301
00:19:09,715 --> 00:19:11,717
You don't have to.

302
00:19:14,553 --> 00:19:15,853
It's yummy.

303
00:19:15,854 --> 00:19:18,924
Isn't it?
You'd never guess by how it looks.

304
00:19:19,791 --> 00:19:22,227
It's foolish to judge things
by their appearance.

305
00:19:23,228 --> 00:19:25,364
Why do you have to say that
with an attitude?

306
00:19:27,599 --> 00:19:30,701
Tell me, how do you say,
"It's delicious" in Korean?

307
00:19:30,702 --> 00:19:31,970
It's "<i>masisseoyo</i>".

308
00:19:32,971 --> 00:19:34,106
"<i>Masisseoyo.</i>"

309
00:19:35,107 --> 00:19:37,175
Then, how do you say, "big sister"?

310
00:19:37,176 --> 00:19:39,411
Big sister? Um...

311
00:19:40,379 --> 00:19:42,481
- It's "<i>eonni.</i>"
- <i>Eonni...</i>

312
00:19:44,016 --> 00:19:45,784
Can I call you "<i>eonni</i>" from now on?

313
00:19:47,819 --> 00:19:49,087
Of course, you can.

314
00:19:58,130 --> 00:20:00,666
These colors are so pretty.
What's this outfit?

315
00:20:01,366 --> 00:20:04,069
It's <i>chima jeogori.</i>
Do you want to try it on?

316
00:20:04,603 --> 00:20:05,971
Can I?

317
00:20:36,468 --> 00:20:37,636
<i>Annyeong haseyo.</i>

318
00:20:39,304 --> 00:20:41,973
You can speak Korean, sweetie?

319
00:20:41,974 --> 00:20:43,709
I learned it from my <i>eonni.</i>

320
00:20:44,243 --> 00:20:47,478
Look at you. You look beautiful in it.

321
00:20:47,479 --> 00:20:48,847
<i>Annyeong haseyo.</i>

322
00:20:50,115 --> 00:20:53,685
Standing right next to each other
like this, you look like real sisters.

323
00:20:55,053 --> 00:20:57,855
If she were still alive,

324
00:20:57,856 --> 00:21:00,892
she would be about her age, wouldn't she?

325
00:21:01,393 --> 00:21:03,561
Have so many years already passed?

326
00:21:03,562 --> 00:21:05,463
Time flies.

327
00:21:05,464 --> 00:21:07,733
Why don't we take your picture?

328
00:21:10,936 --> 00:21:14,039
Are you ready? Look over here.

329
00:21:15,073 --> 00:21:17,175
Say "<i>kimchi</i>"!

330
00:21:37,996 --> 00:21:40,299
- It's so pretty.
- Yes, it's beautiful.

331
00:22:02,487 --> 00:22:04,588
Wow, this is pretty.

332
00:22:04,589 --> 00:22:07,024
Did you paint this, too?

333
00:22:07,025 --> 00:22:07,993
It's the sea in Busan.

334
00:22:08,960 --> 00:22:11,996
Busan? Is that in Korea?

335
00:22:11,997 --> 00:22:14,700
Yeah. That's where my grandpa was born.

336
00:22:15,367 --> 00:22:18,804
And it's my other home.

337
00:22:20,472 --> 00:22:22,107
I've been there several times.

338
00:22:23,709 --> 00:22:26,645
The sea I saw there was so beautiful.

339
00:22:30,082 --> 00:22:33,885
You know what? I want to go to art school.

340
00:22:34,853 --> 00:22:37,189
That's great. You can definitely do it.

341
00:22:41,393 --> 00:22:45,864
It's my dream to pass the exam
and go to Tokyo.

342
00:22:47,265 --> 00:22:50,235
Tokyo is very far, isn't it?

343
00:22:53,772 --> 00:22:55,073
Yes, it is.

344
00:22:56,842 --> 00:22:57,943
It's far.

345
00:23:02,180 --> 00:23:03,315
I wonder

346
00:23:05,050 --> 00:23:07,853
if I can work without any problems.

347
00:23:12,190 --> 00:23:13,325
At times,

348
00:23:14,226 --> 00:23:16,495
I feel like I shouldn't be here.

349
00:23:18,130 --> 00:23:19,464
Do you want to go back?

350
00:23:21,266 --> 00:23:22,267
I'm not sure.

351
00:23:32,744 --> 00:23:34,312
<i>Eonni</i>, you'll be all right.

352
00:23:35,781 --> 00:23:38,083
If you don't like it there,
you can just come back.

353
00:23:39,251 --> 00:23:40,118
I'll be here for you.

354
00:23:44,990 --> 00:23:47,459
Thanks. I'll do that then.

355
00:23:49,995 --> 00:23:50,995
Let's go!

356
00:23:50,996 --> 00:23:52,898
- Let's go!
- Come!

357
00:24:03,208 --> 00:24:04,675
Hi, sweetie.

358
00:24:04,676 --> 00:24:06,945
- Hello.
- You're full of energy.

359
00:24:10,949 --> 00:24:11,983
Mari.

360
00:24:12,617 --> 00:24:15,120
You look so happy. What happened?

361
00:24:16,922 --> 00:24:20,091
You were at Semaul again, weren't you?

362
00:24:21,193 --> 00:24:22,927
What did you eat there?

363
00:24:22,928 --> 00:24:23,829
<i>Beondegi</i>.

364
00:24:24,329 --> 00:24:28,233
And they let me wear
a beautiful <i>chima jeogori</i>.

365
00:24:33,038 --> 00:24:35,140
It's so pretty!

366
00:24:35,774 --> 00:24:37,075
Did she paint this for you?

367
00:24:41,279 --> 00:24:42,747
You're such an amazing girl.

368
00:24:43,949 --> 00:24:47,819
Being able to connect with anyone
is a gift you have, Mari.

369
00:24:50,655 --> 00:24:52,791
Come on, let's have dinner now.

370
00:24:53,525 --> 00:24:54,925
What are we having?

371
00:24:54,926 --> 00:24:57,262
- We're having stew.
- Again?

372
00:25:01,032 --> 00:25:03,467
SEPTEMBER

373
00:25:03,468 --> 00:25:04,836
See you, Mom.

374
00:25:06,371 --> 00:25:07,606
Have good day.

375
00:25:08,440 --> 00:25:09,508
Good morning.

376
00:25:11,776 --> 00:25:13,878
It looks great, Mari.

377
00:25:13,879 --> 00:25:14,813
Thanks.

378
00:25:21,419 --> 00:25:23,754
What are you saying now?

379
00:25:23,755 --> 00:25:26,291
We've had a good time together,
haven't we?

380
00:25:28,793 --> 00:25:31,329
This is smuggling, right?

381
00:25:33,465 --> 00:25:34,766
Mari.

382
00:25:35,567 --> 00:25:37,835
Soohyun is out painting somewhere.

383
00:25:37,836 --> 00:25:38,802
She is?

384
00:25:38,803 --> 00:25:42,774
I don't want to continue doing this.

385
00:25:44,242 --> 00:25:47,012
Please, let this be the last time.

386
00:25:49,548 --> 00:25:52,583
She's probably at the beach.
Why don't you go there?

387
00:25:52,584 --> 00:25:54,385
Okay, I will.

388
00:25:54,386 --> 00:25:56,354
Actually I was.

389
00:26:15,840 --> 00:26:16,908
What's the matter?

390
00:26:18,843 --> 00:26:20,679
It's so cool that you can paint.

391
00:26:23,949 --> 00:26:25,716
Why don't you try?

392
00:26:25,717 --> 00:26:26,985
I'm not good at it.

393
00:26:30,355 --> 00:26:33,358
It's scary at first, isn't it?

394
00:26:34,426 --> 00:26:36,361
But you just make up your mind

395
00:26:39,564 --> 00:26:43,068
that you are going to drop
your own colors on the white canvas.

396
00:26:44,703 --> 00:26:47,706
The most important thing is to decide.

397
00:26:48,573 --> 00:26:49,608
Decide?

398
00:26:56,915 --> 00:26:58,617
You decide your own colors.

399
00:26:59,150 --> 00:27:01,119
You tell yourself,
"I'm going to paint with these colors,"

400
00:27:01,886 --> 00:27:03,555
and dare to put your brush on the paper.

401
00:27:18,536 --> 00:27:19,604
What's the matter?

402
00:27:20,772 --> 00:27:25,276
The color of the sea seems different
from the one I saw before.

403
00:27:28,613 --> 00:27:32,250
Are the colors of the sea different
between Japan and Busan?

404
00:27:35,487 --> 00:27:37,322
It's the same sea,

405
00:27:39,991 --> 00:27:41,693
but the colors might be a bit different.

406
00:28:47,425 --> 00:28:48,293
Mari.

407
00:28:50,428 --> 00:28:52,230
This is for you.

408
00:28:53,565 --> 00:28:56,101
Thanks. That's me, isn't it?

409
00:28:56,768 --> 00:28:58,103
Yes, that's you.

410
00:29:00,271 --> 00:29:03,708
The color is different,
but it's the same sea.

411
00:29:04,442 --> 00:29:05,643
They're connected.

412
00:29:07,278 --> 00:29:11,216
<i>Eonni,</i> I want to go see this sea in Busan
with you someday.

413
00:29:12,250 --> 00:29:14,619
Sure. Let's go together someday.

414
00:29:16,488 --> 00:29:18,456
- <i>Yagsog.</i>
- <i>Yagsog.</i>

415
00:29:28,600 --> 00:29:29,934
It's so scary.

416
00:29:30,735 --> 00:29:32,337
That's why we can't trust them.

417
00:29:35,039 --> 00:29:38,509
My husband was coerced into doing it.

418
00:29:38,510 --> 00:29:42,112
He didn't scheme the smuggling himself.

419
00:29:42,113 --> 00:29:45,049
It's not what you think it is.

420
00:29:47,552 --> 00:29:51,990
- Mom...
- It's a Korean immigrants' store.

421
00:29:53,758 --> 00:29:55,426
Did they cheat again?

422
00:29:56,427 --> 00:29:57,262
Sweeties,

423
00:29:57,896 --> 00:29:59,029
you'd better not go there.

424
00:29:59,030 --> 00:30:02,099
They're Korean immigrants, right?
Did they cause trouble again?

425
00:30:02,100 --> 00:30:03,334
It seems they did.

426
00:30:03,902 --> 00:30:04,869
Come on, let's go.

427
00:30:06,070 --> 00:30:06,938
<i>Eonni</i>...

428
00:30:37,402 --> 00:30:40,871
NOTICE OF CLOSING

429
00:30:40,872 --> 00:30:42,841
<i>As a matter of fact,</i>

430
00:30:43,508 --> 00:30:46,511
<i>Soohyun eonni's father really wanted
to send her to art school.</i>

431
00:30:47,512 --> 00:30:49,547
<i>That's why he needed the money.</i>

432
00:30:55,019 --> 00:30:57,655
Are you still in contact with Soohyun?

433
00:31:04,028 --> 00:31:05,396
I can still feel her hand.

434
00:31:07,265 --> 00:31:08,733
I remember the way it felt

435
00:31:10,668 --> 00:31:11,636
the last time I was with her.

436
00:31:14,739 --> 00:31:15,940
But I'd forgotten.

437
00:31:17,041 --> 00:31:19,544
I'd forgotten about her
and what happened back then.

438
00:31:20,245 --> 00:31:21,779
I lived and grew up...

439
00:31:23,181 --> 00:31:27,585
and became an adult
without remembering most of it.

440
00:31:33,191 --> 00:31:34,425
Oh, I know.

441
00:31:35,059 --> 00:31:36,761
Look at this.

442
00:31:37,328 --> 00:31:38,963
Here. Look.

443
00:31:40,265 --> 00:31:42,033
I bought this
when I went to visit my folks.

444
00:31:42,767 --> 00:31:43,935
It's <i>men jeogori.</i> Isn't it cute?

445
00:31:45,904 --> 00:31:49,908
But you don't let go
of anyone's hand anymore.

446
00:31:54,045 --> 00:31:55,613
I mean,

447
00:31:57,615 --> 00:32:00,418
you keep picking all the crumbs,
don't you?

448
00:32:08,459 --> 00:32:09,694
Thanks a lot.

449
00:32:14,432 --> 00:32:15,833
And you're here for me now,

450
00:32:16,434 --> 00:32:19,404
as if you're picking up your crumbs.

451
00:32:21,472 --> 00:32:22,440
Um...

452
00:32:23,708 --> 00:32:25,243
Well, you know...

453
00:32:28,079 --> 00:32:31,616
I think you have such a lovable,
super-powerful character

454
00:32:32,417 --> 00:32:34,819
even though you can be extremely clumsy.

455
00:32:37,322 --> 00:32:38,222
Oh, shut up.

456
00:32:40,692 --> 00:32:42,961
Oh, no! It's burning.

457
00:32:43,528 --> 00:32:44,362
There.

458
00:32:47,131 --> 00:32:49,367
- Here.
- Thank you.

459
00:32:51,669 --> 00:32:53,071
Here we go.

460
00:32:55,573 --> 00:32:56,574
Thanks.

461
00:33:05,283 --> 00:33:06,651
It's delicious.

462
00:33:10,888 --> 00:33:11,789
This way, please.

463
00:33:14,625 --> 00:33:18,395
I'm sorry for showing up like this
during your busy schedule.

464
00:33:18,396 --> 00:33:21,099
No problem at all. Did something happen?

465
00:33:22,867 --> 00:33:25,837
The group called "Volunteer"

466
00:33:27,839 --> 00:33:31,376
has been on my mind
since the kidnapping incident.

467
00:33:39,450 --> 00:33:42,152
The Volunteer seems to be spreading

468
00:33:42,153 --> 00:33:45,722
a network of collaborators mainly
around the Shinjuku area.

469
00:33:45,723 --> 00:33:49,626
However, we have no clue
what kind of people make up the group

470
00:33:49,627 --> 00:33:52,196
or if they have any particular base
of operations.

471
00:33:53,031 --> 00:33:55,265
With no concrete identity emerging,

472
00:33:55,266 --> 00:33:57,434
it's hard to determine
how to move the investigation forward.

473
00:33:57,435 --> 00:33:59,771
I feel like I'm forced to search
in the dark.

474
00:34:04,742 --> 00:34:06,010
Lieutenant Iiyama,

475
00:34:07,378 --> 00:34:08,846
I want you to keep this between us, but...

476
00:34:10,581 --> 00:34:12,984
Superintendent Toyozumi
of Internal Affairs

477
00:34:16,354 --> 00:34:19,524
is considering placing Lieutenant Agawa
back in the field.

478
00:34:21,726 --> 00:34:23,493
You mean, Lieutenant Agawa? But he is...

479
00:34:23,494 --> 00:34:24,962
It's on purpose.

480
00:34:26,764 --> 00:34:29,567
I think he's bringing him back on purpose.

481
00:34:32,904 --> 00:34:34,405
Will he be placed here, by any chance?

482
00:34:36,641 --> 00:34:40,244
I can't tell what Superintendent
Toyozumi's true intentions are.

483
00:34:40,912 --> 00:34:43,713
But the misinterpretation incident
from four years ago...

484
00:34:43,714 --> 00:34:45,515
EXCLUSIVE SCOOP:
THE DARKNESS INSIDE THE POLICE FORCE!

485
00:34:45,516 --> 00:34:48,386
"DELIBERATE MISINTERPRETATION"

486
00:34:49,220 --> 00:34:51,456
...certainly isn't over in Toyozumi's mind.

487
00:34:54,425 --> 00:34:57,361
That incident isn't over
in my mind, either.

488
00:35:04,035 --> 00:35:07,872
So, tell me, Arikeeno. Do you have
a particular type that you like?

489
00:35:10,274 --> 00:35:11,442
It's so abrupt.

490
00:35:12,243 --> 00:35:15,813
All conversations over alcohol
tend to be abrupt, you know.

491
00:35:17,215 --> 00:35:18,149
Then, tell me

492
00:35:19,250 --> 00:35:21,419
why you chose to become a police officer.

493
00:35:22,120 --> 00:35:22,954
That's abrupt.

494
00:35:25,356 --> 00:35:26,991
See, it's abrupt, isn't it?

495
00:35:30,261 --> 00:35:32,897
All right. I give in and I will tell you.

496
00:35:34,365 --> 00:35:35,365
Do you remember

497
00:35:35,366 --> 00:35:39,203
the "Yoyogi Phantom Killer Incident"
from eight years ago?

498
00:35:41,072 --> 00:35:45,710
To tell you the truth, I happened to be
at the crime scene that day.

499
00:35:51,682 --> 00:35:54,951
I saw this phantom killer
who was wielding a knife.

500
00:35:54,952 --> 00:35:59,790
And he was about to go toward a mother
pushing a stroller with her baby in it.

501
00:36:00,791 --> 00:36:01,626
I decided then.

502
00:36:02,793 --> 00:36:04,695
I don't really know why,

503
00:36:05,296 --> 00:36:06,864
but I thought that I had to protect them.

504
00:36:07,865 --> 00:36:09,500
So, I stood up to him.

505
00:36:11,335 --> 00:36:13,870
But then, the killer

506
00:36:13,871 --> 00:36:15,940
started coming at me,
with his knife raised.

507
00:36:17,508 --> 00:36:19,043
My body froze completely.

508
00:36:21,179 --> 00:36:24,081
Just then, a male police officer
appeared out of nowhere

509
00:36:24,982 --> 00:36:27,251
and saved my life by tackling the killer.

510
00:36:29,921 --> 00:36:30,955
Afterward, this officer

511
00:36:32,323 --> 00:36:33,424
complimented me.

512
00:36:35,760 --> 00:36:38,663
He said, "I don't know how you found
the courage.

513
00:36:39,897 --> 00:36:43,568
Not everyone can face a criminal."

514
00:36:45,703 --> 00:36:47,772
That's why I decided

515
00:36:48,372 --> 00:36:51,275
I wanted to become
a police officer that day.

516
00:36:53,344 --> 00:36:55,980
I wanted to become someone
who could protect others.

517
00:37:06,023 --> 00:37:07,158
Arikeeno?

518
00:37:08,593 --> 00:37:10,061
I had one too many drinks.

519
00:37:10,761 --> 00:37:11,996
What? Are you okay?

520
00:37:15,032 --> 00:37:17,033
- I'm sorry.
- Um...

521
00:37:17,034 --> 00:37:18,836
I should excuse myself now.

522
00:37:22,640 --> 00:37:25,676
I'll give you the money another time.

523
00:37:26,510 --> 00:37:29,080
- I'm so sorry.
- Arikeeno?

524
00:37:40,358 --> 00:37:44,996
EIGHT YEARS AGO

525
00:37:46,764 --> 00:37:48,031
Are you okay?

526
00:37:48,032 --> 00:37:49,733
Call an ambulance.

527
00:37:49,734 --> 00:37:51,869
- Okay.
- Nobody has called one yet?

528
00:37:53,537 --> 00:37:55,706
He was already down when we got here.

529
00:37:56,340 --> 00:37:59,242
Officer Yanagi. Are you okay?
What happened?

530
00:37:59,243 --> 00:38:01,746
A man with a knife... Toward the station...

531
00:38:02,980 --> 00:38:04,749
Don't move. Please stay still.

532
00:38:08,219 --> 00:38:09,287
That scumbag...

533
00:38:10,688 --> 00:38:12,023
He was going for my gun.

534
00:38:15,192 --> 00:38:16,192
Go quickly.

535
00:38:16,193 --> 00:38:19,130
Please stay still. I'm calling backup.

536
00:38:20,131 --> 00:38:21,198
This is an urgent request for backup.

537
00:38:21,899 --> 00:38:25,036
Officer Yanagi has been stabbed
with a knife.

538
00:38:31,742 --> 00:38:34,645
- Good morning!
- Good morning.

539
00:38:37,848 --> 00:38:40,250
<i>From headquarters to all stations.
In Yoyogi Nishi's jurisdiction,</i>

540
00:38:40,251 --> 00:38:43,687
<i>assault on a police officer
and an attempt to seize his gun.</i>

541
00:38:43,688 --> 00:38:46,923
<i>The location is Yoyogi Nishi 2-Chome.</i>

542
00:38:46,924 --> 00:38:51,095
Yoyogi Nishi
falls under Ryo's jurisdiction.

543
00:39:57,962 --> 00:39:59,096
Don't struggle.

544
00:40:02,900 --> 00:40:04,101
Are you all right?

545
00:40:07,238 --> 00:40:09,273
I don't know how you found the courage.

546
00:40:09,907 --> 00:40:11,475
Not everyone can face a criminal.

547
00:40:14,011 --> 00:40:15,479
This way. Please help her.

548
00:40:22,787 --> 00:40:23,721
Handcuff him.

549
00:40:27,358 --> 00:40:28,526
Oda.

550
00:40:35,900 --> 00:40:39,569
What the heck did you do to him?

551
00:40:39,570 --> 00:40:41,471
Stop! Hey!

552
00:40:41,472 --> 00:40:43,039
How dare you!

553
00:40:43,040 --> 00:40:44,241
What are you doing?

554
00:40:45,643 --> 00:40:46,544
Do you hear me?

555
00:40:48,012 --> 00:40:50,280
<i>That's why I decided</i>

556
00:40:50,281 --> 00:40:52,016
<i>I wanted to become
a police officer that day.</i>

557
00:40:53,984 --> 00:40:56,620
<i>I wanted to become someone
who could protect others.</i>

558
00:41:11,302 --> 00:41:12,203
Oda.

559
00:41:15,506 --> 00:41:17,007
What got into you today?

560
00:41:21,345 --> 00:41:23,314
I'm a failure as a police officer.

561
00:41:26,250 --> 00:41:27,184
What?

562
00:41:29,820 --> 00:41:32,423
Officer Yanagi is a true police officer.

563
00:41:35,993 --> 00:41:38,863
Stabbed three times, he still
wouldn't let the perv take his gun.

564
00:41:46,504 --> 00:41:47,705
On the other hand, I...

565
00:41:50,307 --> 00:41:52,743
I totally lost it
when I saw you covered in blood.

566
00:41:57,047 --> 00:42:00,017
When I found out
that it was Officer Yanagi's blood,

567
00:42:06,590 --> 00:42:07,725
I was actually relieved.

568
00:42:22,740 --> 00:42:23,574
Ryo.

569
00:42:27,545 --> 00:42:29,780
I don't want to be an obstacle for you.

570
00:42:39,023 --> 00:42:40,357
But I can't hold back anymore.

571
00:42:46,664 --> 00:42:48,032
You are more important to me

572
00:42:50,267 --> 00:42:51,535
than anyone else.

573
00:42:57,708 --> 00:42:58,576
I'm sorry.

574
00:43:16,093 --> 00:43:17,494
ORIGINAL STORY BY KUROMARU

575
00:44:01,038 --> 00:44:05,976
LIEUTENANT HIROYA AGAWA

576
00:44:09,013 --> 00:44:11,515
<i>Miss Koda finally has a partner?</i>

577
00:44:12,082 --> 00:44:13,816
Let's make money together again.

578
00:44:13,817 --> 00:44:15,985
I will investigate
and expose him this time.

579
00:44:15,986 --> 00:44:18,021
Our division will have a handful for sure.

580
00:44:18,022 --> 00:44:20,089
<i>If you involve Sergeant Koda,</i>

581
00:44:20,090 --> 00:44:21,791
I won't forgive you this time.

582
00:44:21,792 --> 00:44:23,494
You begin to see the last mountain

583
00:44:24,461 --> 00:44:25,929
you can climb.

584
00:44:27,965 --> 00:44:28,966
<i>He's the one from...</i>
